gov.nasa.jpf.jvm.bytecode

Class INVOKECLINIT

  • java.lang.Object
    • gov.nasa.jpf.vm.Instruction
      • gov.nasa.jpf.jvm.JVMInstruction
        • gov.nasa.jpf.jvm.bytecode.InvokeInstruction
          • gov.nasa.jpf.jvm.bytecode.INVOKESTATIC
            • gov.nasa.jpf.jvm.bytecode.INVOKECLINIT
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    InstructionVisitorAcceptor, Cloneable

    public class INVOKECLINIT
extends INVOKESTATIC
    this is an artificial bytecode that we use to deal with the particularities of calls, which are never in the loaded bytecode but always directly called by the VM. The most obvious difference is that execution does not trigger class initialization. A more subtle difference is that we save a wait() - if a class is concurrently initialized, both enter INVOKECLINIT (i.e. compete and sync for/on the class object lock), but once the second thread gets resumed and detects that the class is now initialized (by the first thread), it skips the method execution and returns right away (after deregistering as a lock contender). That's kind of hackish, but we have no method to do the wait in, unless we significantly complicate the direct call stubs, which would obfuscate observability (debugging dynamically generated code isn't very appealing).
